05418nam a22006615i 9780773597198DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20152015xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735971987 a10.1515/97807735971982doi  a(DE-B1597)656538  a(OCoLC)1159181395  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aDS195b.M37 2015 7aHIS0550002bisacsh04a956.622231 aMarchand, Laure, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTurkey and the Armenian Ghost :bOn the Trail of the Genocide /cLaure Marchand, Debbie Blythe, Guillaume Perrier. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTranslator’s Preface -- tForeword -- tNote on Turkish Pronunciation -- tTimeline -- tIntroduction: The Armenian Genocide and the Law -- tMarseille: Little Armenia -- tArmen Aroyan, Archeologist of the Genocide -- tOf Grandmothers and Grandchildren -- tConverts: The Hidden Armenians -- tDersim: Land of Rebels -- tGenocide of the Stone -- tThe Armenian Don Quixote -- tVakıf: The Last Village -- tFootball Diplomacy -- tAn Obsession with Denial -- tSevag Balıkçı: 1,500,000 + 2 -- tÇankaya Palace: The Republic’s Original Sin -- t“If You Destroy a Nest, You Can’t Make It Your Own” -- tThe Soul of the Resistance Movement -- tHrant Dink: The Armenian and His Turkish Heirs -- tThe Kurds: Pricking Turkey’s Conscience -- tDeath of a Sub-Prefect -- tThe Righteous Turks -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe first genocide of the twentieth century remains unrecognized and unpunished. Turkey continues to deny the slaughter of over a million Ottoman Armenians in 1915 and the following years. What sets the Armenian genocide apart from other mass atrocities is that the country responsible has never officially acknowledged its actions, and no individual has ever been brought to justice. In Turkey and the Armenian Ghost, a translation of the award-winning La Turquie et le fantôme arménien, Laure Marchand and Guillaume Perrier visit historic sites and interview politicians, elderly survivors, descendants, authors, and activists in a quest for the hidden truth. Taking the reader into remote mountain regions, tiny hamlets, and the homes of traumatized victims of a deadly persecution that continues to this day, they reveal little-known aspects of the history and culture of a people who have been rendered invisible in their ancient homeland. Seeking to illuminate complex issues of blame and responsibility, guilt and innocence, the authors discuss the roles played in this drama by the "righteous Turks," the Kurds, the converts, the rebels, and the "leftovers of the sword." They also describe the struggle to have the genocide officially recognized in Turkey, France, and the United States. Arguing that this giant cover-up has had consequences for Turks as well as for Armenians, the authors point to a society sickened by a century of denial. The face of Turkey is gradually changing, however, and a new generation of Turks is beginning to understand what happened and to realize that the ghost of the Armenian genocide must be recognized and laid to rest.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArmenian Genocide, 1915-1923xHistoriography. 0aArmenian Genocide, 1915-1923. 0aArmenian massacres, 1915-1923xHistoriography. 0aArmenian massacres, 1915-1923. 0aArmeniansxHistoryxTurkey. 0aArmenianszTurkeyxHistory. 0aCollective memoryxTurkey. 0aCollective memory. 0aGenocidexTurkey. 0aGenocidezTurkey. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Turkey & Ottoman Empire.2bisac